@ahankinson is this  behavior specified in the DRF docs anywhere? I can't seem to find it. It seems like the key is omitted from the output not if the value is None but if the corresponding key was not present in the input. For example:

```py
from rest_framework import serializers

class Foo(serializers.Serializer):
    foo = serializers.ReadOnlyField(required=False)

>>> Foo({'foo': None}).data
{'foo': None}
>>> Foo({}).data
{}
```
To match that behavior might be a little more difficult given how serpy is currently designed.

One question:

What's the reason for adding < or > before every value (s/u/f/b <width>) in the format string, and not just at the beginning of the format string? It would be great if you can give an example of when this functionality is required. A machine is little or big endian, it does not change endianness for every value in a bit field. =)

Some background information about the byteswap() function:

I often use bit flelds in c data structures. Although the c standard of bit fields is not well defined, and compilers may implement in different ways, I would like to be able to decode them with this module. In the example below the value of 'b' is stored in memory as bit 0 in buf[1] and bits 3-7 in buf[0]. To decode this with this module I have to use the byteswap-function to buf before trying to decode it with the format string "u3u6u7". Of course, it's impossible to handle this case with < and >, since you don't know that it is a 16 bits container. It should as well be a 32 bits container. The format string does not contain this information.

    #include <stdio.h>
    #include <stdint.h>
    
    struct foo_t {
        uint16_t a : 3;
        uint16_t b : 6;
        uint16_t c : 7;
    };
    
    int main()
    {
        uint8_t buf[2];
        struct foo_t *foo_p = (struct foo_t *)buf;
    
        foo_p->a = 2;
        foo_p->b = 0x3f;
        foo_p->c = 0;
    
        printf("0x%02x 0x%02x\n", buf[0], buf[1]);
    
        return (0);
    }
    
    Compilation and execution on a little-endian machine.

    $ gcc main.c && ./a.out
    0xfa 0x01

Hi @mtgtnt!

There were some adjustments made to the select behavior [last year](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/commit/7385ed4bf1bb5c719aaa4a10c4b43783f5a755ac) (in v2.28.12) to get the filter to properly work with [jQuery UI selectmenu](https://jqueryui.com/selectmenu/).

You don't need to target every column. The `filter_excludeFilter` can target the header class name as well:

```js
$(function() {
  $("table").tablesorter({
    widgets: ["filter"],
    widgetOptions: {
      filter_excludeFilter: {
        ".tablesorter-header": "range"
      }
    }
  });
});
```

Related to [issue #1520](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/issues/1520#issuecomment-370782677)... I can look at the code again and see if I can fix it to use the "exact" filter type directly instead of only using it when a user includes an "or" or "and" in the query.

